OrderedCollection[ATRejectedSubmission{#id:'6bad0c8e-248c-480c-a3bd-e71236007d7a',#title:'The Stack of Local Representations on a Coadjoint Orbit: A Categorical Approach',#authorName:'Franco Cazzaniga',#authorEmail:'franco.cazzaniga@uninsubria.it',#abstract:'We construct a stack R of local stabilizer representations over a coadjoint orbit O of a compact Lie group G, verify the descent conditions explicitly, and show that the G-action on global sections recovers the classical representation theory via geometric quantization. \r\nThis provides a stack-theoretic interpretation of the Kirillov orbit method and the Borelâ€“Weil theorem.',#assessment:'1) Category: Research preprint\n2) Aims: The text aims to construct a stack of local stabilizer representations over coadjoint orbits and demonstrate its connection to classical representation theory through geometric quantization at a technical level.\n3) Correctness: No errors identified\n4) Coherence: Adequate\n5) Consistency: Consistent\n6) Semantic opacity: Moderate (Justified complexity)\n7) Novelty: Original\n8) Bibliography: Incomplete\n9) Effectiveness: Partially achieves aims\n10) Cross-framework traction: Medium\n11) Claims: Partially supported\n12) Contribution: Substantive\n13) Structure: Minor issues\n14) Integrity: No issues\n15) Code (if provided): Not provided\n16) Editorial outcome: Potentially suitable with revision\n\nThe paper presents a technically sophisticated construction connecting stack theory to representation theory through coadjoint orbits. The mathematical framework is coherent and the central construction appears sound, though several key steps in the verification of descent conditions and the connection to geometric quantization require more detailed exposition. The bibliography lacks sufficient coverage of relevant work in both algebraic geometry and representation theory, particularly missing connections to existing categorical approaches to the orbit method. While the main claims regarding the stack-theoretic interpretation are plausible, the supporting arguments need strengthening, especially the explicit verification of descent conditions mentioned in the abstract. The structure suffers from compressed exposition that obscures important technical details. The work represents a substantive contribution to the categorical understanding of classical representation theory, but requires revision to adequately support its claims and provide complete context within the existing literature.',#verdict:#review,#rejectedAt:DateAndTime['2026-01-04T16:46:48.05385+01:00'],#originalSubmittedAt:DateAndTime['2026-01-03T23:59:28.879858+01:00'],#localPdfPath:'/Users/Franco/Dropbox/ai-theoretical.org/data/rejected-pdfs/6bad0c8e-248c-480c-a3bd-e71236007d7a.pdf'}]